  "response": "The speed of an electron depends on the context and environment. Here are some key points:\n\n1. Orbital electrons in atoms:\n- Typically move at speeds around 1-2 million meters per second\n- Velocity varies depending on the electron's energy level and atomic structure\n\n2. Free electrons:\n- Can travel close to the speed of light (99.99% of light speed)\n- In a conductor, electrons move at drift velocity, which is much slower\n\n3. In a vacuum:\n- Electrons can approach the speed of light (299,792,458 m/s)\n- Near-light speeds are achievable in particle accelerators\n\n4. Average electron speed in a wire:\n- Typically very slow, around a few millimeters per hour\n- Electrical signal propagates much faster (near light speed)\n\n5. Quantum mechanics perspective:\n- Electrons behave as probability waves\n- Their precise speed and location cannot be simultaneously determined exactly\n\nThe specific speed depends on the electron's energy, environment, and context of observation.",
